===Etymology===
From the {{etyl|fr|en}} {{m|fr|grognard||grumbler}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ɡɹɔnjaɹ/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# An [[old]] [[soldier]].
# {{lb|en|games|slang}} Someone who [[enjoys]] playing older war-games or roleplaying games, or older versions of such games, when newer ones are available.
#: ''James is such a '''grognard''', he only plays the original edition of Dungeons and Dragons.''
#* {{seecites|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adjective}}
# Anyone of a legacy way of doing things might refer to him or her self as being a grognard within that group; see also "old school" or "O.G." Example: an artist who works with paints and brushes instead of using digital mediums; a drummer who plays a standard drum kit and avoids an electronic one; an audiophile that prefers vinyl LPs instead of CDs or other modern storage media.
